The paper discusses compressed sensing and its application in imaging devices such as magnetic resonance imaging, radio-interferometry, and ultra-sound imaging. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT), Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV), Signal Processing (cs.SP), Multimedia (cs.MM), or Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-categories. The paper specifically focuses on a new random sampling approach that involves projecting the signal over blocks of sensing vectors, which is relevant to both image processing and signal processing. Therefore, cs.IT, cs.CV, and cs.SP are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also provides theoretical results on the number of blocks required for exact sparse signal reconstruction, which is relevant to numerical analysis. Hence, cs.NA is also a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper includes examples of Gaussian measurements and time-frequency bases, which are relevant to multimedia. Therefore, cs.MM is also a possible sub-category.
